segments.text: And what town is near San Carlos?
And what year were you here in Texas?
She got married after she got here.
How old were you when you left Mexico?
But 19 is 19 and 10 is... You were born in 1881 and you came, left Mexico in 1910.
So you were nearly 30 years old.
For what reason do you come here to the United States?
Life in Mexico is very expensive.
And what kind of work do you have in Mexico?
In the city of Iropuato or near?
That's the name of the town.
When did you come to Texas?
Where did you live in the first place in 1910?
I lived in a shop called Tomelope's.
I was working in a farm in Medes.
But here, when did you come here?
I was sowing all over the place.
I was working in the railroad for about five years.
And then I learned how to work the cart, how to work the cart.
There is a lot of work in the cart.
It was very hard at that time.
Now there is machinery to work naturally.
Before you could work with pure strength.
And for what reason do you come to Texas and not from California or another part of the United States?
It's more immediate to go to Texas.
To go there it's very, very far.
And in what way do you come?
One comes to Laredo and pays one or two reales and they let him go home.
They paid one or two reales to go to this side.
And for what reason do they come to Bryant?
We came to live here and then we bought the house here.
We bought the house here and we were working very hard.
I went to Hueas and from there I brought 200, 300 pesos and with that we lived here.
I had a lot of family.
And where did you meet your wife?
Where did you meet your wife?
And why were you in Franklin?
And from Mexico, I came here.
In what year did her sister come here?
For what reason did she come here?
They came to look for work to live more.
And how did they get here?
No, in those years it was by train.
In Laredo, there are men who hire people and bring them here.
And that's how they get here.
And are there problems with the revolution in your town when they come to the United States?
When we came here, they only paid one for the bridge, you know, two reals, and they only paid one for this.
The children come here and don't come back.
I haven't returned to the banks of the river.
Life is very hard over there.
Life is very hard over there.
All you can do is plant corn.
Plant corn with mules, in the middle of the field.
We moved here and it was very comfortable because I had a big family and we made ourselves live better.
Did you come with your family or alone?
Do you have relatives there at the airport?
I had, who knows now, for so long, already 92 years.
And you never came back to visit there?
Because I didn't like it there anymore.
You like life here in the United States more?
Yo me ganaba muy buen dinero.
Tenía como, creo que eran tres, ¿no?
Eso fue después que nos casaron.
Cuando él entró para acá, andaba solo.
And your money was paid by whoever did the work.
And you, you lived in your town during the revolution, right?
Do you remember anything like this?
He tried to go to the capital.
But in the haciendas there were groups of soldiers.
And they were the ones who were doing evil.
They tried to take away the rich man.
To give him to the poor.
They killed cows, sheep, and the meat was distributed to the people who were in the farm or town.
But your family spent all this time in your town, right?
They didn't go to the United States.
And are there soldiers in your town?
During the Revolution, were there soldiers in your town?
Well, in each place there was a group of soldiers because they kept the enemies from entering.
And what kind of work did your father have?
I was very young when he died.
I was four when my father died and I wasn't eight when my mother died.
And after that, who do you live with?
Do you want to talk to her?
It's to make the history of the people who live here in Texas better.
I don't know what to say.
I know that I live better here than in Mexico.
I live better here than in Mexico.
I can tell you that I know many parts of Mexico, but I don't like it.
Well, there's life, but there's no work.
If you want to live, you have to live a very poor life.
In Mexico, they give jobs to men aged 20 to 40, 45.
Then, if they have to live, they live.
A young boy, there is never work.
He has to walk around the street selling tortillas, selling this or something to get a cent.
Yes, but is there a lot of work here?
He's the only boy that's here.
Sometimes he's here, sometimes he's there.
Is he a relative or just a friend?
Does he live here with you?
And what year did you come here, Brian?
And for how many years did you live near Franklin?
And what kind of work did you have there?
I used to work in the farm.
At first, you know, take care of the cows.
I worked in the farm, lived in the farm.
Do you want me to speak to you in Spanish?
Let them hear what you're saying.
You come here, you came here...
From the city of Acuña, Coahuila.
And is it the town of your mom and dad?
The city of Victoria, in the city.
And why did you come here?
Well, first of all, I came... Well, there's something I shouldn't say.
I don't have a father in Mexico.
My mother lives with another man.
When I got to my age, I couldn't live with them.
I understood that I couldn't live with them.
Well, I came here to look for my life.
And did you have relatives here in Texas?
Yes, I have relatives in San Antonio.
They are from my mother's house.
But I liked it here in Texas, how I worked.
My bosses liked how I worked.
The work I did, they paid for it.
I had money to spend, to go whenever I wanted.
And I never went back to Mexico.
I want more Texas than Mexico.
It's not that I'm not Mexican, I am Mexican.
I'm more imposed here than there.
And for what reason do you come here?
Did you come here to work?
I came to work, to make my life.
But why did you come to Bryan, not San Antonio or San Marcos?
Well, I was in different towns.
I was in San Angelo, Abilene, in many towns.
I didn't distinguish a town, just because.
When I came here to Bryan, all the people here saw me very well.
I have a lot of friends and they love me as much as I love them.
We've always been one for each other.
I'm not leaving this town until I die.
There aren't many Mexicans like San Antonio.
But it's more peaceful than San Antonio.
It's smaller and there are fewer people.
It's much more peaceful than San Antonio.
I lived in San Antonio without my parents.
I liked this town and I think I'm going to stay here.
What kind of work do you have?
I don't have work to do right now.
He's from here, I'm from there.
I should do what he does and I do it.
With the time I have to be here, I never learned to work in Mexico.
I didn't know how to work in Mexico because I never worked.
This is where I learned to work.
If I came to Mexico, I would ask for work there.
The work that I have here, they didn't give it to me.
They wanted me to start from the bottom and then I would get to the top.
I didn't even doubt it for about 15 years so that I could do it.
But in Mexico now there are more opportunities for people than in the past?
Yes, for those who have a school, yes.
But is it necessary to have a school?
But the people who don't have a school can't do anything.
I only had six years of school.
There are people who have 12 years.
Young people who have, like the families of those who can't have money, they send them 12 years, and they have a good job.
When they finish school, they finish 20 years, and they get a good job.
I'm very happy to be here in Texas.
Well, not just here in Texas, but all over the United States.
If I wasn't here, I'd be in another state, like I was in my family.
Is life very different here in Mexico?
In what way is it different?
With the same job, in what way is it different?
No, no, no, in another way, not the job.
But in another way, in another way it's different.
In another way I can't like Texas.
Because there are a lot of festivities, a lot of festive days.
And all that, you walk around and everything.
Here no, here it's just the weekend, the sun.
between the week and the weekend.
Every month we have a day, a holiday day.
Mr. Lopez, are there a lot of parties in Mexico during these years when you lived there?
Were there many parties in Mexico in the past?
People would dance and enjoy the dance.
There aren't any here, but they're different.
People do it as they're used to it.
In your town, Mr. Lopez, in your ranch, what day of the year is the most important holiday?
What's the day of the flag?
What's the day of the flag?
Christmas Day, all the December fruits, all days, all nights.
Pastors all come to worship the Virgin of Guadalupe.
Y cuando usted estaba muy joven, viene a... Usted vive en rancho.
En rancho se llaman... La Hacienda de Guadalupe.
Is it on the side of the mountains or the sea?
No, no, it's close to Monterrey and Nuevo León.
Well, I know Linares and Monterrey.
At four in the morning, I would leave the house to get to the church at eight.
In those years there was no voice.
And they had nothing on foot.
¿Y qué fue el pueblo más cerca de su hacienda?
Son dos pueblos, dos ranchos juntos.
Uno está en un lado del camino y el otro al otro lado.
Tome López grande y Tome López chico.
Y usted salió a los Estados Unidos antes de la Revolución?
The Pancho Villa revolution was going on, so I came here.
So I came here, and I haven't come back, not even to the shore of the river.
I don't like it there anymore.
You've been here for more than ten years.
I'd like to go back to Mexico.
She doesn't like it there anymore.
It's very hard to live here.
Pero durante estos años de la revolución, ¿su familia tenía problemas o no?
No, había soldados en el pueblo.
En el pueblo, en cada esquina hay uno.
They are there with their lanterns in the corners.
Who knows now, but now everything is more populated.
When I was there, in every corner there was a gendarme.
With his lantern, day and night.
Who knows how it will be now?
I don't give him any reason.
From Mexico to the edge of the river, from the edge of the river to here.
And what kind of house did you live in in Mexico?
A house made of adobe, made of earth.
Two, three rooms, the kitchen and everything.
How many people lived in your ranch in Mexico?
No, it was a lot of people.
One was Tome López Grande and the other was Tome López Chico.
They were like here, but there was only the street.
And over there was a ranch and over here was another one.
There was a lot of people.
How many children do you have?
And each child has six, seven, five... Oh, you have many grandchildren.
And 16... How do you say it?
You are the second wife of...
And your first wife is from Mexico or from here?
Do you marry her after you come to the United States?
Look how she brings the boots.
Didn't she tell you what she did with the boots?
Le dije que fuera a poner la junta del calentón, ya ves como andan mojadas ayer.
He pones clothes to the heater pa que se sequen.
He put them on top of the heater.
